04982nam a22007575i 9780271084398DE-B159720220524034747.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220524t20212019pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97802710843987 a10.1515/97802710843982doi  a(DE-B1597)583855  a(OCoLC)1103917543  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 7aREL0330002bisacsh04a200.94/090222304aThe Sacred and the Sinister :bStudies in Medieval Religion and Magic /ced. by David J. Collins, S. J. 1aUniversity Park, PA : bPenn State University Press, c[2021] 4cÂ©2019  a1 online resource (304 p.) :b6 illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aInspired by the work of eminent scholar Richard Kieckhefer, The Sacred and the Sinister explores the ambiguities that made (and make) medieval religion and magic so difficult to differentiate. The essays in this collection investigate how the holy and unholy were distinguished in medieval Europe, where their characteristics diverged, and the implications of that deviation.In the Middle Ages, the natural world was understood as divinely created and infused with mysterious power. This world was accessible to human knowledge and susceptible to human manipulation through three modes of engagement: religion, magic, and science. How these ways of understanding developed in light of modern notions of rationality is an important element of ongoing scholarly conversation. As Kieckhefer has emphasized, ambiguity and ambivalence characterize medieval understandings of the divine and demonic powers at work in the world. The ten chapters in this volume focus on four main aspects of this assertion: the cult of the saints, contested devotional relationships and practices, unsettled judgments between magic and religion, and inconclusive distinctions between magic and science.Freshly insightful, this study of ambiguity between magic and religion will be of special interest to scholars in the fields of medieval studies, religious studies, European history, and the history of science.In addition to the editor, the contributors to this volume are Michael D. Bailey, Kristi Woodward Bain, Maeve B. Callan, Elizabeth Casteen, Claire Fanger, Sean L. Field, Anne M. Koenig, Katelyn Mesler, and Sophie Page.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 0aGood and evilxHistoryyTo 1500. 0aMagiczEuropexHistoryyTo 1500. 7aRELIGION / History.2bisacsh1 aBailey, Michael D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBain, Kristi Woodward, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCallan, Maeve B., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCasteen, Elizabeth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCollins, David J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCollins, S. J., David J., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aFanger, Claire, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aField, Sean L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKoenig, Anne M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMesler, Katelyn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPage, Sophie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn State University Press Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311074520740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780271084398?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780271084398423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780271084398/original  a978-3-11-074520-7  Penn State University Press Complete eBook-Pac